prompts.text: (full body, full shot:1.2), a realistic and detailed photo of a nerdy 22-year-old goth girl with glasses
(full body, full shot:1.2), a realistic and detailed photo of a nerdy 22-year-old goth girl with glasses

Welcome to perfect HD

This workflow is capable of creating HD quality 8k images, 25mb+ i don't know how much more it can do, my 12gb card is limited there.
You are not limited to 8k, anything lower works just as well.

With IP adaptor and now reactor, this can reliably copy a person likeness while following your prompts.. This can allow some very creepy things IMO with nudity. Be responsible and don't share photos of real people in situations you would not want to be put in.  

V1.0
 - fixed faces not working for multiple people
 - fixed padding issues that came up rarely but caused improper blending
 - fixed face detection drop size being too large, made drop size a main option due to its usefulness
 - face parts enhance each option on its own now.  Can do just 1 eye, or just mouth.
 - added custom subject paste back to avoid bad paste orders on some photos.
 - added 1 extra aux detailer because we all know why you need 2 :P
 - added reactor face swap, it's not great on 8k but decent on others
 - added model upscale option
 - added Downscale for all previews, so my browser would stop freaking out.  Turns out having 10 8k previews makes it freak out.

Features
 - XL or 1.5 base generation - LCM used can be removed.
 - 2 base models - 2 extras for use with enhancers
 - Full upscale with 1.5
 - Full subject cutout and enhance
 - Decent hand fixing with meshgraphormer
 - Full face with hair cutout enhance
  - inner face enhance
  - face features enhance (eyes, nose, mouth)
 - Aux detector to enhance something else (breasts, clothing, etc)
 - All enhancement steps use cutouts to avoid full scale renders 
 - Any relevant areas have optional inpainting
 - Any relevant areas have optional IP adaptor Refs
 - All areas have separate prompts/Lora
 

Notes to come in future releases - Hopefully It's fairly straight forward to follow.

Notes on use

Disable any groups from beside the model loaders, All groups after the first main upscale are optional turn everything off below that

Set prompts/ip adaptor loras... Image size/ models/ LCM etc.
1. Run the workflow and get a decent image result from the upscale. 

IF your image has hands and you want to try to fix them.  This is not always needed.
Enable Hand fixing Detections only, run the workflow to get a preview image or an error.
 - If it detects things enable the Enhance hands step, if not you can play with the settings or bypass this step

Next is subject detections but there is an important upscale before this.  This is a default 4x upscale that you can change to what you want or can handle
 - This is important because it determines the final image size. 

By default this generates a 720p  1280x720 image as base  then 1.5 upscale to 1080p 1920x1080 for the upscale step
Now it upscales this by 4x for 8k final image  If wanting 4k, 2x if wanting, 1440p 1.5x

This image it creates is important as it is the base background.  Subjects can be enhanced to look very detailed still at 8k without rendering an 8k image.  

Each step after this shows a base image size and a render size in its options.  
This is determined by the final image size and allows you to rescale the massive 8k/4k images to things your system can handle. 
Original size is the size you will be pasting on, render size is the size you will render at and upscale before pasting in back
Going to high on size is bad, going too low is bad.  You need to set the upscale for each part seperate to ensure its a good size for quality and able to be run by your system.
When doing 8k you DO NOT need to match the size of the images.  Go as high as you can, but you will be surprised when render size is 1/2 or even 1/4 original for things like body.  

Next enable subject detections, run the workflow, Check the image preview masked
 - If its ok enable subject enhance, use IP/lora/prompts

Next is aux detector, this can detect things like breasts, clothing, or many other things depending on what model you use.
 - if using this just enable detections like before.  Run the flow and get settings correct for your detection. 
 - Then enable the enhance step and run.  

Next is the face detection
This is split
1 model masks the head with hair and the other masks the face itself.  This is because it offers more detailed faces.  Both or either can be used.
 - Faces usually detect fine but just like before check your preview masks and then enable the enhance steps.

Next is Face Parts Detections.  
Enable detections first to ensure open pose can make a proper mask.
 - If it can you can then prompt to eyes/mouth/nose separate and enable the enhance step.

Done.

Default detectors needed
Full head
https://civitai.com/models/326568/anzhcs-head-segmentation-prototype-or-yolov8-or-adetailer-model

hand detector
https://civitai.com/models/329458/hand-detailersegmentation-adetailer

Control nets
hand controlnet - makes bare hands
https://civitai.com/models/262788/controlnet-handrefiner

This can be used to give gloves.
https://civitai.com/models/9868/controlnet-pre-trained-difference-models

Reactor face swaps the subject with your cropped ref face.

2 places to do this here 

1st is before the inner face upscale, this rarely holds through the upscale but can help shape things

2nd is before the face parts, this hold quite well and allows changes.

Can do neither, one or both
Padding is touchy, if no problems with masks overwriting, a larger padding helps blend better, but in photos with multiple people its best to keep this as small as you can.

If 1 person, disabling seperate subjects is a bit faster and can prevent bad detections making things go bad.


If 2 or more subjects
If your subject's Bboxes overlap, it can cause issues with the blending back to the original.  
If this is the case, disable the Separate Subjects, and it will render the subjects together, allowing it to blend them properly.

Same thing for AUX detecters

This is not always needed, but it was really pissing me off I could not choose the order of the paste subjects, as some images did not work with the default top to bottom pasting.

I have added to the default paste by mask used by the rest of the workflow because the subjects have an issue when doing multiple people.  

Paste by mask pastes top to bottom only.  This causes issues when 1 subject mask is much wider than the other.  (arms out, or 2 people in 1 while one in other... etc.) As the smaller mask can cut out much more than just itself, as it needs to match the size of the other.  

The only bypass I found was to separate the masks and paste them back separately, and not rely on the mask mapping from the node.

By default, this uses paste by mask as normal, so if it works you need to change nothing.  But if you notice the problem mentioned above, this area allows you to rearrange the paste work to ensure the masks don't overwrite the wrong spots.

Just enable the paste group, and then only enable the number of masks you need to paste. (up to 4) (8 for face)
You order them with the text boxes, remember they come in top to bottom, so 1 is top most, 4 is bottom most.

Notes on detectors

Models
Any models really work change them out and see what you can detect

Bbox and sub threshold

Lower these if nothing is detected, raise them if too much is

SAM - SAM is available for any non seg models.  If you have a seg model it tends to work well without it.  Connect SAM if you need to for any detector

*********  DROP SIZE   ******

This is a great option, allowing you to drop certain detections smaller than the number.  This can remove background people detections, remove bad detections all around.  It's the first thing I use when the mask is decent but has extra things I don't want.  I set default to 20.  Then if I need it, it can go up to 600 or so.  Keep raising it until you're it removes what you want to remove.

Padding is a fickle one... With one person any padding is good if its blending well, higher blends better but takes longer to render.  With more than one person in the photo you should take care on how high you go with this as the larger the padding the more likely you will need to use the custom pasting as it will detect close people.  At padding 0, it blends poorly.  2-4 works well for multiple people.

You can play with any of the other settings all you want, but most are not touched by me for the most part.

Notes on initial generations

Ensure you set all models correctly for your use
LCM lora, Upscale model, detection models, controlnet models, ip adaptor models, clip vision, etc...

All models can be connected to the start areas for each group set.  You can change or add any nodes in the models area and just connect it to what you want to use it on.
You can use 1 model for base, 1 for upscale, 1 for aux, and one for face..  

Loras and IP are separate for each step.  Set each as you need for the area being worked on.

XL works decent for base/upscale as does 1.5 either can be used

IP adaptor is strong, if you want to change things but keep the person, start the base ip adaptor at 0.4 at 0.8 strength.  This will give your prompt a good head start before it starts morphing the person into the person you ask for.
Prompt clothing and hair and any other things you want

You can change the model for IP adaptor i prefer plus, but all have uses.  The xl models are needed for xl ip adaptor
You can change the ip adaptor stuff if you know more about it than i do.  I tried the composition and style stuff... i just could not get good results

Separations of masks should all be disabled if you are rendering 1 person.  More than one can use it to cut down on render times
